  "base_commit": "89f42497a9951fbb72ce087dc813ed9973f9e686",
  "pr_number": 1896,
  "issue_number": 1689,
  "issue_title": "Bug: existing user can lose access to original family/account after upgrade + family sharing flow",
  "issue_body": "## Bug description\n\nA self-hosted user reported that after upgrading from `v0.6.7-alpha` to `v0.7.0-hotfix1`, adding an existing second user account (wife) into a family-sharing setup caused the wife's original account context to disappear and all visible accounts to become the husband's.\n\nThe user had **two separate users on the same instance** before the upgrade. After adding the wife's account into the husband's `Family`, the wife's prior data appears to have either:\n- been reassigned into the husband's family,\n- been orphaned under the previous family, or\n- had the original user row destroyed while the historical family/account data may still remain.\n\nThere is concern that **~5 months of transactions** may now be inaccessible.\n\n## Likely related history\n\nThis appears closely related to the long-standing bug where inviting a user who already belongs to another `Family` can move them into the new family and strand or destroy access to the original one.\n\nRelevant prior work:\n- #978 (closed, not merged): \"Fix account destruction when user switches families via invitation\"\n- #1171: Check for pending invitations before creating new Family during SSO log in/sign up\n- #1173: Enforce one pending invitation per email across all families\n- #1272: Family sharing\n\nDuring triage, we noticed PR #978 still contained a `@user.destroy` path, which raises the possibility that some flows may still destroy the original user record instead of safely preserving/restoring it.\n\n## Reproduction outline\n\n1. On a self-hosted instance, create user A with Family A.\n2. Create user B with Family B.\n3. Upgrade from `v0.6.7-alpha` to `v0.7.0-hotfix1`.\n4. Add user B into user A's family-sharing setup, expecting B to see both A's and B's accounts.\n5. Observe that B instead appears to lose access to B's original family/accounts and now sees only A's accounts.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nIf an existing user who already belongs to another family is added to a sharing/family flow:\n- their original family and data should remain accessible,\n- the app should not silently reassign or destroy their original account context,\n- and any sharing flow should be explicit about whether access is additive vs. rehoming the user.\n\n## Actual behavior\n\nThe invited/added user's visible account set becomes the inviter's/husband's family, while the original wife-owned family data becomes inaccessible.\n\n## Recovery angle\n\nIn the reported case, recovery may still be possible if the prior `families` row and `accounts.family_id` records still exist and only the `users.family_id` link was changed. We suggested read-only SQL to inspect:\n- matching `users` rows by email (including any `+family...` preserved-email variant),\n- associated `family_id` values,\n- whether the old family still has accounts,\n- and related `invitations` rows.\n\nIf the old family still exists, recovery may be as simple as reassigning the correct user row back to the original `family_id`, but we should confirm whether the destructive path is still reachable in current migration/sharing flows.\n\n## Environment\n\n- Self-hosted\n- Upgrade path: `v0.6.7-alpha` -> `v0.7.0-hotfix1`\n- Two pre-existing users under the same instance\n\n## Request\n\nPlease investigate whether there is still a path in current family-sharing/invitation flows that:\n1. reassigns an existing user from their original family into another family unexpectedly, and/or\n2. destroys the original user record instead of preserving/restoring it.\n\nA regression/spec around multi-user self-hosted upgrade scenarios would probably be worth adding here.\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-27T21:25:46.000Z",
